constructor and moves all observer registration logic afterwards.

entry.content:
This patch should effectively be a no-op, replacing one flag

`ExperimentalRenderer` by another `DanglingUntriaged`. Both

currently share the same value, but a different meaning.



Kalvin applied the MiraclePtr rewrite in the renderer process:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4904523

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1GmGagDZtxHpWXJDKqlmzSaqaO5D-pavfH5IRGITfANs/edit#heading=h.s23pazuno76f



1. Rebase and apply the instrumentation CL

2. Compile the compiler: ./tools/clang/scripts/build.py --without-fuchsia

3. Run all the gtests. You can use this script.

4. Concatenate all the output_*, `filter`, `sort -nr`, `uniq`.

5. Install and run https://github.com/ArthurSonzogni/chrome-dangling-ptr-apply-edit

6. Run git cl format

7. Run git checkout origin/main -- base/allocator/partition_allocator/pointers/raw_ptr_unittest.cc

entry.title: Fix build when Windows SDK path has spaces.
entry.content:
Fixing this is a bit tricky, because defining commands for toolchains

and defining commands for custom actions is done a bit differently.

Commands for toolchains are simply defined as a string, and arguments

containing spaces need to be quoted and/or escaped as necessary. On the

other hand, commands for custom actions are specified as a list of

custom arguments, with no special escaping required.



In addition, GN has special handling for {{}} in arg lists. Something

like:

args += [

"{{include_dirs}}"

]

is only expanded later when writing the actual output (i.e. build files)

and expanded into one argument per include dir. However,

args += [

"${win_toolchain_data.include_flags_imsvc}"

]

is evaluated as soon as it is encountered, and just remains as a single

argument.



This problem was not initially discovered, since:

- the majority of Chrome devs use the bundled Windows SDK, which only

passes a single argument.

- and not all targets are broken, e.g. the chrome target itself had no

issues.

However, when using the locally-installed version of the Windows SDK

instead, multiple include dirs are passed, and things like the nocompile

tests and rust bindgen steps break.



As GN does not seem to have a facility for escaping strings for the

command line, setup_toolchain.py now emits a string version and a list

version for any variables that contain a logical list. While this is

really only needed for include_flags_imsvc, it seems more consistent to

uniformly implement this for all variables containing lists.

on pending commit RFHs to be processed.

entry.title: Move partition_alloc into a "partition_alloc" dir.
entry.content:
This patch moves:

"base/allocator/partition_allocator/..."

into:

"base/allocator/partition_allocator/src/partition_alloc/...".



This tried to keep it as minimal as possible. Interesting follow-ups

will happen outside of the rename.



Context:

--------

To protect against UAF, we want to make the PartitionAlloc library

embeddable by some third_parties: pdfium, angle, dawn, swiftshader, ...



PartitionAlloc do not declare yet where is its "include_dir". It means

third parties must put the library files under

"base/allocator/partition_allocator", even if they do not use "base" and

would have liked to put it inside their "third_party" directory.



We would like to make PartitionAllocator behave like a regular library.

It should be importable using:

#include



That's why we are using: "src/partition_alloc"



This implements step 1 of:

1. Move from files under `src/partition_alloc/`

2. Declare PartitionAlloc GN include_dirs.

3. Update the dependants to use #include

entry.title: Fix eagerly loading lazy images on window.print() in an iframe
entry.content:
Document::WillPrintSoon() calls LoadAllImagesAndBlockLoadEvent() on the

LazyLoadImageObserver associated with the Document itself. It's however

that StartMonitoring/StopMonitoring does. Also pass the Document itself

along so that the appropriate set of Elements can be selected.



This doesn't fix the issue in the bug completely, but it fixes an

obvious issue that will at least allow for a better workaround to be

used.

entry.title: [iOS] Only activate-on-foreground one tab when more are batch-opened
entry.content:
When many tabs are opened simultaneously, it does NOT make sense

whatsoever for all of them to be moved to the foreground immediately,

because ultimately, only one tab would be in the foreground, substitut-

ing all other tabs foregrounded before it.



Therefore, this CL updates the method `OpenDistantSessionInBackground`

so that if `load_strategy` says `ALWAYS_NEW_FOREGROUND_TAB`, only one

of them would be opened in the foreground. This behavior tallies better

with the method name `Open..InBackground.` The parameter name is also

updated to `first_tab_load_strategy` for accuracy.



This solution also fixes the issue that `remoteTabsViewController` may

be opening infinite number of tabs on the foreground (with the current

behavior that all of them being brought to foreground right after the

respective web state was created, the "lazy load" approach would not be

applicable.)



Also `OpenDistantTabInBackground` is renamed for accuracy - depending

on `loadStrategy`, it might open the tab on the foreground.

entry.title: viz: pass swap_trace_id to trace a frame submission
entry.content:
Pass swap_trace_id from viz thread to gpu and back to

track the flow of the frame submission.



It was chosen to use SkiaOutputSurfaceImplOnGpu::PostSubmit

as it calls to different gpu output device implementations.

That specific point helps to avoid adding this

trace event to different implementations. Moreover, that's

the point where calls to different backends to swap buffers

is called. Happens on the gpu thread.



SkiaOutputDevice::FinishSwapBuffers was also chosen as it's

called by all the gpu implementations after swap is finished.

Happens on the gpu thread.



In case of the sw path, SoftwareOutputSurface was chosen as

the common point.



PS all the backends are free to use FrameData::swap_trace_id

to extend the flow of the trace. My next CL will contain such

a change for Ozone/Wayland.

entry.title: Reapply "[//cc] Add MappableSI path to OneCopyRasterBufferProvider"
entry.content:
This CL adds a new path to OneCopyRasterBufferProvider that uses

MappableSharedImage rather than GpuMemoryBuffer. The new path is

protected by a base::Feature that is disabled by default. The gist of

the change is that rather than creating a GpuMemoryBuffer, mapping that

in, and then later creating a SharedImage from it, the new path directly

creates a MappableSharedImage (via the new CreateSI() entrypoint), maps

that in, *and* additionally uses it in the same ways that the SI created

from the GMB is being used.



One subtlety is that the GMB is created with the size of the

StagingBuffer, while the SharedImage for the StagingBuffer in its

current creation point in CopyOnWorkerThread() is created with the

`resource_size` param passed to PlaybackAndCopyOnWorkerThread(). Thus,

we would want the MappableSI for the StagingBuffer to be created with

"both" sizes. Fortunately (and as one would expect), the StagingBuffer

is initialized with the `resource_size` param, so the two sizes are

guaranteed to be the same [1].



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:cc/raster/one_copy_raster_buffer_provider.cc;l=295-297?q=CopyOnWorker&ss=chromium



NOTE: This CL is a reland. Differences from the original:



* We avoid the addition of an instance variable (`use_shared_memory_`)

that is accessed from multiple worker threads in racy ways, instead

passing that information locally on each thread.

* We handle the case where CreateSharedImage(..., BufferUsage) fails,

which is now a possibility following changes in the implementation of

that function.

entry.title: Fix GetPendingScaleFactor
entry.content:
This CL fixes the regression issue caused by CL:4744148.



When the double-buffered scale factor is not set by shell,

`SurfaceTreeHost::GetPendingScaleFactor` returns

`host_window_->layer()->device_scale_factor()` as a fallback.

But before the initial commit (i.e., before `host_window()` is added to

the widget), because host_window() is not attached to any root window,

`device_scale_factor()` just returns the default value (1.f).



Therefore, this CL makes `GetPendingScaleFactor` return the scale factor

of the pending target display when the host_window() doesn’t have parent

&& pending_scale_factor_ is not set.



BUG=b:296950585
